  • Mary Miller 02/22/2012 12:52 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:39 PM

Monday, January 1, 1940

Too tired today to do any serious work on Trimorphodon but did enter in maps and ledgers all of last years rattlers - quite a job. Philip left for Schenectady this evening.

-----------------------------------

(June 8, continued)

irrigates area is paved. The rest looks like excellent country. Drove 51 miles up this road. Men stopped and ate supper; took it easy waiting for darkness. Warm. Moon in first quarter. No wind. Conditions fine; results terrible.

Started south at 7:35 (MST). Waited 2 mi S. until 8 for darkness. From there for the next 24 miles drove at 10 miles an hour with boys riding the fenders. Didn't see a thing. Certainly wouldn't have missed even a small snake. They just weren't out, yet the territory looked fine in day time. Must be wrong time of year. Hunted toads at Rio Frio Bridge 1.4 mi N. of Rock Springs, and got a number. Woodhousii and punctatus were calling.

Moon set at 9:40. Rode fenders from 8:15 5o 10:30. temp at just 87 degrees F.

(continued on Jan 2)

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 02/24/2012 12:57 PM
  • Mary Miller 02/22/2012 01:01 PM
  • Mary Miller 02/22/2012 12:59 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:39 PM

Tuesday, January 2, 1940

Nothing done tonight - too tired.

----------------------------

(June 8 Cont. from Jan 1)

Fell gradually as we rode to 78 degrees.

Arrived at Phoenix at 11:30. Plenty sore. Total miles today 334; night drive 49 miles; 3 1/2 hours.

Arm is nearly well; but thumb is still very tender and bothersome.

Page Edit History:
  • Mary Miller 02/22/2012 01:04 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:39 PM

Wednesday, January 3, 1940

Nothing done tonight.

--------------------------

(June 9 continued)

The war reports are terrible today.

Stopped at Ransom's Auto Court. Took a shower and wired home.

Thumb still sore and very inconvenient. Called on Arrington. He gave me a Rhinocheilus and a worm snake He had 2 Chilomeniscus from Tucson.

Went around to the University and saw Flock. Lee Arnold wasn't there and couldn't be located.

Caught a solare near Ransom's in the street at 5 pm.

Left Ransom's for the evening drive at 7:45. Still glow in the west. Went north on Florence Road 17 miles.

1 Leopard Lizard DOR 9 mi S of Oracle Junction

Then rode the Sabrino Canyon Road to end of the pavement.

1 salvadora DOR Wright's town
1 Leopard Lizard DOR Wright's town

Returned to Tucson at 11 pm thoroughly disgusted. Never had

(continued on Jan 4)

Thursday, January 4, 1940

Worked all evening on statistics of differences.

-------------------------

(June 9, continued from Jan 3)

a worse night. Conditions were ideal. No wind. Temp 85-86 degrees. 1/3 moon until 10:40.

Todal miles today 265; evening drive 97; elapsed time 3:25.

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 07/02/2014 03:25 PM
  • Mary Miller 02/22/2012 01:12 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:39 PM

Friday, January 5, 1940

Movie tonight.

Revel worked on Trimorphodon scale rows.

--------------------------------

(June 10 continued)

Hunted in rocks and mesquite at Cabo bi Trading Post, 12 mi N. of Sells and got some good lizards, but there were no chucks.

Got a collared lizard at Quijotoa

Hunted at Tracy's Store (= San Simeon) and got some good lizards. Uta ornata are found on mesquite limbs.

Got a cally 10 mi W. of San Simeon and a whiptail 15 mi w.

Got to Ajo about 1 pm. Pretty hot. Had had trouble with a leaky tube, the same one fixed at Phoenix, and had to buy a new one. Had been coasting along on a soft tire since Tracy's.

Left Ajo at 2:20 and reached Yuma at 6:50. Hunted at one point N. of Ajo but found no chucks. This road up to Gila Bend is too barren to be much good. We decided to go on rather than to try to drive it at night. It was very hot between Ajo and Yuma. We stopped in the Gila Mtns and got 4 more

(continued on Jan 6.)

Notes:

Mary Miller

Laura - not sure what's after Cabo bi on January 5. Kindly review.

Saturday, January 6, 1940

Spent a part of the morning going over the worm-snake paper with Abbott.

Spent the rest of the day and evening on the Trimorphodon paper and made good headway. It really begins to look like a paper.

------------------------------

(June 10 cont from Jan 5th)

chucks.

Arrive at Yuma at 6:50 MST.

Left Winterhaven for the evening drive at 6:50 PST. Just after sunset 96 degrees.

1 red racer DOR L Fields 2 mi @ of Winterhaven

Not quite dark at Calexico branch

1 Coleonyx COR 15 mi E of Calexico 90 degrees
1 Sonora m linearis DOR 7 mi E of Calexico
1 Sonora m linearis DOR 5 mi E of Calexico
1 Sonora m linearis DOR 2 mi E of Calexico
1 Sonora m linearis DOR 2 mi E of Calexico

All of these were in irrigated territory. All were saved.

1 gopher COR 5 mi E. of Calexico 8:59 88 degrees
1 longnose COR 4 mi E. of Calexico 9:08 88 degrees
1 woodhousii COR 5 mi W. of Calexico
1 Sonora m linearis 5 mi W of Calexico
1 marciana DOR 5 mi W. of Calexico
1 red racer DOR 6 mi W. of Calexico

(Continued on Jan. 7)

Notes:

lwilliams

What sps. is marciana??

Sunday, January 7, 1940

Worked all day on Trimorphodon and again made good progress. Really looks as if it would shape up. Left on the 7:30 train for Los Angeles. Had expected to drive up tomorrow morning but too much rain.

--------------------------

(June 10, cont. from Jan 6)

1 red racer DOR Signal Mt. PO
1 magister DOr Signal Mt. PO
1 gecko COR 2 mi S. of Seeley

Reached Seeley at 10:30 and El Centro at 11:03. Had a hard time finding a good auto court in the dark and picked a bad one.

Miles today 426
Miles evening drive 48; 3 1/2 hrs.

Saturday, January 20, 1940

Spent part of the morning on the worm-snake paper; found a lot of changes.

Then went over to the zoo and checked over the Trimorphodon paper with Perkins. He had a number of good suggestions and corrections.

Then came back and worked over these. Found Los Angeles specimens quite queer - this required a lot of checking, changing and working over.

Page Edit History:

Sunday, January 21, 1940

Revised the Trimorphodon paper b/c of the queer specimen from Arizona. Gave it another careful going over. Also gave the worm snake paper another going over and made many minor changes. Planned the figures. This took all day.

In the late afternoon and evening worked on the census. Finished the entries but didn't tackle the summaries.

Saturday, February 17, 1940

Spent the day and evening on the rattle paper and made some progress. The body is finished except some odds and ends; and the bibliography.

Shaw worked today on hemipenes; and Devel on his lizard key. He also gave me data on 2 ruber taken this morning 2 mi N. of Murray Dam.

1 Found in granite pile under large slab, with about 6" of body in sunlight. East facing slope. Day clear, warming (66 degrees) at 10:15 AM. No breeze.

2 On west-facing slope at 1:25 AM. Just outside of a granite-covered cave (extending back for 3 feet) in bush, shaded by boulders forming the cave. Temp 66 degrees. Clear day.

Saturday, May 4, 1940

Today went out in the back country with Allen Chickering. A cool and cloudy day. A little warmer and clear part of the time in the back country. The itinerary was Broadway, Spring Valley, Jamul, Lyon's Valley, Barrett Dam, Cottonwood, Campo, Jacumba, Mt. Spring, Back to Boulevard, (ate lunch), Laguna Junction, Laguna Mt, Cuyamaca, Julian, Banner Grade, Scissor's Crossing, 3.3. mi S, back up San Felipe Valley to Warners where we stayed all night. It was obviously too cold to warrant a night hunt so we turned in early.

Saturday, May 11, 1940

This afternoon went over to the laboratory of Morgan Eastman at Ocean Beach and made tests on rattlers with his calibrated neon stroboscope. It didn't work as well as I had hoped. Could get the larger ones ok but not the smaller because they wouldn't rattle regularly or continuously enough. Only got one - a small cinereous.

The results: (Temp 77 degrees)

L cerastes long string 34.9
cinereous M Calyeatria 48.0
cinereous Albuquerque 10 c 51.8
cinereous Albuquerque 9 + 1 50.0
cinereous Albuquerque 6+ 50.8
cinereous Albuquerque 2c 56.9
oreganus Arbeckle long str. 47.4

Sunday, May 19, 1940

This morning went out to Corte Madera for lunch. 44 miles. Nothing seen.

This afternoon at 5:20, toward the eastern edge of the Corte Madera Valley there was a small oreganus on the road. Put a stick on his head and picked him up, or started to. In some way which I will never understand he got enough of his head loose to bite me on the inner side of the right thumb above the upper joint. Both fangs, but probably got very little venom as he was small and had already bitten the stick.

I jerked my hand loose and got a tourniquet on (necktie) at once. The pain was evident in the thumb instantly.

Started to drive on and then went back (about 1/4 mile) and collected the snake.

There was some pain in the arm pit at 5:27.

Drove as fast as possible in spite of the Sunday traffic. Drove as far as El Cajon myself; gg drove the rest of the way.

Loosened the tourniquet at 5:25 and at 5:26 for about 1/2 minute each time.

First noticed a tingling and numbness in the upper lip at 5:50; this spread to

(continued on May 20)

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 07/02/2014 04:32 PM

Monday, May 20, 1940

Left the hospital in the afternoon. Feeling weak and shaky. Some swelling in the arm - not much pain.

----------------------------

(May 19 continued)

the tongue and lower lip. It was very noticeable at 6:10.

Reached El Cajon about 6:15 and called up Dr. Knox. He came over to his office above the drug store and made a deep cross-incision at the site of the bite and got a good flow of blood. However his suction apparatus wasn't working and it took 15 or 20 minutes to get it in order, and even then it didn't seem to do much good. The tourniquet was removed and I don't think was replaced until I reached the hospital.

He tested me for horse serum, found I was sensitive and thought I had better not take a shot until I was desensitized. I had him call up Crawford and then went on in to Mercy Hospital where Drs Mark Young and H A Thompson were waiting to see me. From here on the symptoms are worth very little, being complicated.

(continued on May 21)

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 03/01/2012 12:31 PM
  • Mary Miller 02/28/2012 10:45 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:39 PM

Tuesday, May 21, 1940

Still in bed suffering from serum reaction; very bad hives on arm.

---------------------------

(May 19, Cont. from May 20)

by the results of the treatment.

a) tourniquets (later applied to forearm), then to upper arm as a red streak became evident clear up to the arm-pit. This later turned yellow.

b) incision. This did considerable damage to the ball of the thumb.

c) serum. This caused a very severe case of hives and other bodily reactions.

Crawford came in shortly. Was desensitized and given 5cc of serum in the lower arm and the other 5cc in the upper arm. More suction was applied and rubber tourniquets. Was typed but not given a blood transfusion.

Arm and thumb very painful notably on account of the treatment, not the bite. Some swelling in the arm pit and the facial symptoms continued.

Was given dope and got some sleep intermittently.

1 gopher L COR 1 mi S of Imperial Dam
6:50 (PST) 90 degrees a little after sunset. Brush - river.

Then went back to Yuma and ran the San Luis look. Went fast as there was evidently nothing out.

Saturday, June 8, 1940

At Yuma
Up and away to breakfast at 6:05 PST.
1 Yuma King snake DOR 2 mi S. of Yuma orchard
Reached Laguna Dam at 7:10 PST and hunted snakes on the island. The boys turned over boards, debris, rocks, cow chips in great numbers. It is clearly evident that the snakes are not as plentiful as in the winter when Wallace Wood hunted them. Cy got 3 Sonora's, 1 under a board and 2 under cow chips. We were on the island about an hour. Uta stans, Uta ornata (on trees) and whips were very thick. Hunted at a point 2 mi. N. of Laguna Dam and got a chuck and some utas. This from 8 to 9 PST.

Went back and started east from Yuma. Hunted in a small rocky hill 5 mi SE of Yuma but there were no chucks. Dips 8 04 12 mi SE of Yuma.

Hunted chucks in the Gila and Mohawk mts. got 4 in the former.

Arrived in Phoenix at 4:30. Hot. Put up at La Fiesta Auto Court. Had a puncture from a nail.

Drove out the new River Rock Creek Road to look it over. Only a small part in the

(continued on Jan 1.)

Sunday, June 9, 1940

This morning we got away from Phoenix at 8:30. It was a cool day at this time of year.

We first stopped at Evans place. He had nothing unusual.

We finally started east from Tempe at 9:50. Went to Apache Junction and then up the Roosevelt Lake Road as far as Canyon Lake. Object chuck-a-wallas, but we didn't get any as it was too late in the morning and too hot. The boys hunted hard at 3 places. chucks were seen at one - signs at the other. A few lizards were collected 10 mi. N. of Apache Junction.

Returned to Apache Junction and had lunch. At the zoo they had one of the black chucks; also reds all said to be from near Canyon Lake. Tried to buy them but they wanted too much.

Came south to Tucson via Florence Junction, Florence, Coolidge and Picacho, arriving at 4 pm. Hunted for dips just north of Florence. No luck. Too hot. Bufo alvarius DOR at Randolph

(continued on Jan. 3)

Monday, June 10, 1940

This morning I got out at 5:50 and drove up to Oracle Junction alone to see if I could get some DOR's. No luck. One buzzard was flying along the road. Back at 6:50, 43 miles.

Got started from Tucson toward Ajo at 7:45; clear and warm.

Picked up a solare at Ajo Junction.
Whiptails were seen 10, 15, 20, 21, 23 miles W of Tucson. The 2nd or 3rd was seen to have black throats.

Caught a solare at Roble's Ranch 25 mi W of Tucson, Pima County (where road branches to Sasable). Also noted Callisaurus here.

Callys noted at E boundary Papago Indian Reservation (= San Pedro, Pima County).

Hunted at 8:45 at the end of the pavement and got a whiptail. Call it San Pedro. Already too late for the best hunting.

Holbrookia 6 mi E of Fresnal; also at Sells. Tried rocks for chucks but there were no signs. Got Holbrookia and Uta ornata at Sells.

Got a solare on the road at 9:40, 5 mi

(continued on Jan 5)

Sunday, June 16, 1940

Shaw worked today and made some headway in the rat's nest in the basement where incoming specimens have been overflowing into every corner.

I continued catching up with recording, filing, entering trips of others in this book and similar activities. This is fairly up to date. Must soon return to research; whether I can concentrate on it remains to be seen. these days its purely an escape mechanism - nothing else. Don't seem to be able to concentrate on anything except the most mechanical calculations.

Today marks the last real resistance in France.

Sunday, August 18, 1940

Today Chickering and I took a trip through the back country. Warm and pleasant.

First to Scissors Crossing via Lakeside, Ramona, and Julian - 2 mi S. of Scissors Crossing; back to Julian; Cuyamaca, Laguna. Did considerable cruising back and forth on top of the ridge. Home via Laguna Junction, Pine Valley, Descanso, Japatul, Glen Lonely, Dehesa, Jamacha, Sweetwater, National City.

Start 8 am, Return 5:30
1 pacific rattler DOR L Laguna trees
1 banded racer DOR L Laguna trees

Only a few lizards out
209 miles; all in SD County

Sunday, August 25, 1940

Worked all day on the Fisher Moment System, much longer than I had expected but it was worthwhile as I made some notable simplifications with almost no loss of accuracy. This will save much time in the future whenever this system is used. And I think it is preferable to Geary and Pearson as they don't give P exactly.

Mary Miller

Saturday, December 14, 1940

Miscellaneous work this morning including a call at the Natural History Museum and the zoo. Too much going on during this week to have any time to call there.

Not feeling up to original work these days have started copying the trip records for 1940 into the proper books on Form 31C. has to be done sometime anyway so might as well do it now when the mood and energy for research are not available.

The scale counts at the Natural History Museum didn't work out so no one is working on anything except Shaw. I am not sorry as I simply haven't the time or energy for proper supervision.

Lampropeltis getula

California King snake

L.g. boylii refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a ringed pattern.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
